-- BHP, Commonwealth, Telstra, Westfield, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-11-02T21:16:58Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-02/bhp-commonwealth-telstra-westfield-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December
gained 0.3 percent to 4,714 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank
of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 2.2 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  climbed 0.1 percent to 4,701.40.  Mining shares: Copper futures for December delivery gained
1.3 percent to $3.833 a pound at 10:01 a.m. in New York.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, slipped 0.1 percent to A$42.27 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts gained 1.9 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
lost 0.3 percent to A$82.71 in Sydney.  Oil producers: Crude for December delivery rose 1.2 percent
to $83.90 a barrel in New York, the highest settlement price
since May 3.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, declined 0.4 percent to A$43.60.
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) fell 0.3 percent to A$12.67.       Commonwealth Bank of Australia  (CBA AU): The nation’s
biggest home lender will raise its standard mortgage rate by
almost double yesterday’s central bank increase to the benchmark
interest rate, a move condemned by Treasurer Wayne Swan as a
“cynical cash grab.” The lender’s shares gained 1.8 percent to
A$50.19.  Telstra Corp.  (TLS AU): Australia’s biggest telephone
company is seeking an auction of radio frequency spectrum needed
to develop advanced mobile phone services by 2012, the
Australian Financial Review reported, without saying where it
got the information. Separately, Telstra was raised to
“overweight” from “neutral” by analysts at HSBC Holdings Plc.
The stock retreated 0.4 percent to A$2.67.       Westfield Group  (WDC AU): The company will split its A$9
billion of Australian and New Zealand shopping centers into a
new retail property trust, which will raise as much as A$3.5
billion through a capital raising today, the Australian
newspaper reported, without saying where it got the information.
Westfield shares advanced 1.9 percent to A$12.81 before being
halted yesterday.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Shani Raja  in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
